sect2.para:
Although there is no universally accepted single definition, empathy is generally defined as the accurate understanding and acknowledgement of another person’s mental experience, from their frame of reference (Sinclair et al.,
            2017
         ). The ability to achieve empathy with a range of people varies among the general population (Banissy et al., 
            2012
         ), but a natural affinity for empathy is often a factor
            factor
          in why people pursue training and careers that involve clinical interviewing. Empathic ability can be further developed through environmental interactions, practice, and training (Abramson et al., 
            2020
         ), but ultimately in clinical encounters, empathy is an interpersonal process that must be deployed with responsive timing and nuance. This may require a clinician to activate similar mental representations as their client, to exert cognitive control to shift attention away from one’s own perspective, and to activate perspective-taking abilities (Abramson et al., 
            2020
         ).

Relatedly, when a client receives accurate empathy in a clinical interview, it may itself have therapeutic effects (Finn et al.,
            2012
         ). For example, when a client shares their experiences and feels understood by a clinician, it can reduce feelings of isolation and stigmatization while increasing hope and self-understanding (Wampold, 
            2015
         ). Empathy may also increase client adherence to clinical recommendations
            recommendations
          (Riess, 
            2017
         ). If they feel understood, accepted, and validated, they may be more open to behavioral change (Rogers, 
            1995
         ; Shapiro et al., 
            2018
         ). Further, greater empathy is also associated with reduced medical errors and malpractice claims (Riess, 
            2017
         ) as well as greater professional quality of life for clinicians (Laverdière et al., 
            2019
         ). Thus, empathy provides clear benefits for clients and clinicians, if clinicians can develop and activate it.

Biases may promote empathy or impede it. Research indicates that empathy may be more naturally evoked when we interact with those who we perceive as like us, such as being of the same race (Armstrong,
            2017
         ). However, clinicians are trained to become aware of their biases and are cautioned to avoid premature assumptions of empathy (“I’ve had that happen to me” or “I’ve assessed clients with similar cultural backgrounds”), as confirmation bias can prevent soliciting important information (Weiner & Auster, 
            2007
         ).
